<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-780-222  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 780 222.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Executive  Summer 1990 v3 n3 p5(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Document image processing: its strategic role in informationprocessing. (includes related article on the history of documentimage processing)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ryan, Dwight.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>American business is being swamped by paper because there are nomeans to manage the paper produced during the business day.andP;  Everyday half a million sheets of paper are added to the pile.andP;  Thelife cycle of a paper document consists of active use, archive,and destroy.andP;  An automated document management system has manyadvantages: only one copy of each record is maintained in the database, which is accessible to all who need it; multiple keyrelations to help locate a document; available sooner; and costsavings.andP;  Document Image Processing connects islands ofautomation: the paper filing system, printers, fax machines,copiers, and file cabinets.andP;  A company that is planning toimplement image processing capabilities should not compromiseimage processing speed and functionality.andP;  If users cannot findthe documents they need quickly, they will not use the system.andO;The key areas are resolution, the accuracy of the presentation onthe screen; presentation, the ability to see the entire documenton the screen at one time; and performance, page access and pageturning rates.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Image ProcessingDocumentationManagementInformation Storage and Retrieval.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>